olor=#00CCFF>(10/29/01 4:50:13 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: &quot;Rezzes and You&quot;, brought to you buy Wakarez(t</span><hr size=1> I think that Gaeaan posted this tidbit here (in the Flames section) BECAUSE of the sarcastic rant nature of the post, so admonishing him for it's placement might not be the best example of someone's situational prowess. <br>
<br>
And as far as any assumptions that he &quot;became a cleric to help people&quot; goes, there is a basic flaw in that theory.  We became clerics because of the abilities of the class and the potential to make a good group great.  Rezzes, heals and buffs are the main tools employed by clerics but are by no means the only ones.  Clerics can solo quite often if given the right circumstances and available zone mobs.  (And if it goes sour, we can just rez ourselves! )<br>
<br>
We became clerics because it is our nature to help others - our friends and groupmates as well as to roleplay as a character &quot;with divine goodness&quot;.   (Ever since my days of Gary Gygax' D&amp;D games my main character has ALWAYS been a cleric.  After 20 odd years of doing it, I'm damned good at it too.)<br>
<br>
But this does not mean that we have to help every single Norrathian who trudges our way with corpse and/or sad story in hand.  The time spent (notice the careful choice of verb) in EQ is of paramount importance - it's my two and a half year investment in effort.  How and when we spend our time helping others is our choice.  There is no rule which says that &quot;all porting/rezzing classes MUST help others&quot;.<br>
It's a choice we make - and not by ANY means a requirement.<br>
<br>
The balance we strike up when we choose to be a buffing/rezzing cleric is that we are limited in both combat and travel abilities.  Naturally, these two types of characters should want to support the other since we are always looking for the other's help. <br>
<br>
Right?  Right!<br>
<br>
